What I wish I knew when I started using R

Coding Club

June 29, 2017

Trick 1: A proposition of workflow

  1. Use R-projects within R-studio
  2. Use git and github (integrated in R-studio) to save versions of you scripts and enable to return to older versions within your project. On top of that github allow sharing and collaborating.
  3. Structure your project in a logical way eg. 3.1 folder data that contains the raw data 3.2 one script to create usable datafiles from the raw data 3.3 one script (or a folder with scripts) that contains the functions you will be using often. 3.4 folder with R-notebooks to do your analysis and exploration. Every notebook starts with loading the required packages for the session and loading all datatables and functions using the source() command. 3.5 folder with output documents that can be ignored by git.

notebooks: interactive coding that shows graphs and output from analyses between the code chunks. Automatically generates a nicely output in html format that can be sent to external people.

Source: runs all the code from an r-file you call. write as: source(name_of_R_script.R)

Trick 2: Using the tidyverse

dplyr, tidyr, ggplot2, best tools to work with large datasets. Have a look at the many nice cheatsheets. tidyr make data tidy for using in dplyr, using this structure you can use ggplot2, even in interactive mode with plotly. ggplot2 is the best for data exploration. For publication-ready figures base plot function may be better.

Trick 3: The predict function

You fitted a model and you want to get the model predicted values.

dat <- data.frame(x=runif(100,-2,2))
dat$y <- rnorm(100,1+2*dat$x,1)
m <- lm(y~x,dat)

#before
pred <- coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*dat$x

#after
pred_p <- predict(m)
pred == pred_p

Trick 4: Create functions

Create functions when using always the same code. Example with a plotting function to plot (ggplot2) specific columns in a dataframe. Learned through googling and stackoverflow, we will have a session on this coming soon!

visvar <- function(Var,data){
  g <- ggplot(data,aes_string(x="Treatment",y=Var))+geom_boxplot()
  return(g)
}

dat <- data.frame(Treatment=gl(n = 3,k = 10),Value=rnorm(30))
visvar("Value",dat)

We continued with a discussion of using for-loops, see this blog post, but beware of efficiency issues, one could also use the __ply functions (see ?apply, ?plyr etc)

Trick 5: Vectorization

R automatically does operations on entire vectors.

x <- rep(1,10)
y <- rep(2,10)

#without vectorization
for(i in 1:10) print(x[i] + y[i])
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
## [1] 3
#with vectorization
x + y
##  [1] 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3
#beware of internal R tricks
x + c(1,2)
##  [1] 2 3 2 3 2 3 2 3 2 3
x + c(1,2,3)
## Warning in x + c(1, 2, 3): longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
##  [1] 2 3 4 2 3 4 2 3 4 2

Trick 6: Ifelse

A useful function, return specific values depending on a logical statement. This is a vectorized ifelse statement which is faster than writing a loop.

x<-runif(10,-2,2)
ifelse(x<0,"Yes","No")
##  [1] "No"  "No"  "No"  "Yes" "No"  "Yes" "Yes" "No"  "No"  "No"

Trick 7: Functions as object

Functions are object like everything else and can be passed around, like functions within functions, more on this in a further session.

f <- function(n){
  return(rep(10,n))
}
f(10) + 1
##  [1] 11 11 11 11 11 11 11 11 11 11

Trick 8: Logical statement as numbers

In R you can compute stuff from logical, for instance if you want to count how many element in a vector are bigger than 10 you can use:

(x<-rpois(10,10))
##  [1]  9  5 10  9  8 14 10 11  7 12
sum(x>10)
## [1] 3

Trick 10: model.matrix

This is a similar function that gives you the model matrix from a formula, very useful if you want to go deeper into simulations and understanding of linear models.

dat <- data.frame(Treatment=gl(n = 3,k=10),Light=runif(30))
(modmat <- model.matrix(~Treatment*Light,dat))

Trick 11: shinyHeatmaply

Have a look at this package for interactive construction of heatmaps.

Other option for similar plots pairs.panels in the psych package or corrplot in the corrplot package

#example 1 with psych
library(psych)
pairs.panels(matrix(rnorm(100),ncol=10))

#example with corrplot
library(corrplot)
corrplot(matrix(rnorm(100),ncol=10),is.corr=FALSE)

Trick 12: with

Please dont use attach! Use rather the with function which tells R where to look for some variables, it avoids you to use $ or [].

dat <- data.frame(x=rnorm(10),y=rnorm(10))
with(dat,cor(x,y))
## [1] -0.1187447

Trick 13: by

Apply a function to chuncks of data, similar to tapply, dplyr and others 

dat <- data.frame(x=rnorm(30),y=rnorm(30),Treatment=gl(n = 3,k = 10))
#get the maximum from the x column
by(dat$x,dat$Treatment,max)
## dat$Treatment: 1
## [1] 1.233624
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## dat$Treatment: 2
## [1] 1.830944
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## dat$Treatment: 3
## [1] 1.402927
#get the mean per treatment 
by(dat[,1:2],dat$Treatment,function(x) apply(x,2,mean))
## dat$Treatment: 1
##         x         y 
## 0.0452227 0.2747563

## dat$Treatment: 2

##          x          y 
##  0.2974303 -0.5838823

Trick 14: Quickly update your models

From a fitted model you can easily remove (-) or add (+) variables and compute a new model, all in one line. Update works this way: (i) provide a fitted model (model_1), (ii) specify how the model formula should change, you can use the symbol . which means all variables.

dat <- data.frame(x1=rnorm(10),x2=rnorm(10), x3=rnorm(10), x4=rnorm(10), y=rnorm(10) )
F1 <- formula(y ~ x1 + x2 +x3)
model_1 <- lm(F1, data=dat)
# you can add or remove variables from the object with 'update()'
model_2 <- update(model_1,.~.-x3)
model_3 <- update(model_1,.~.+x4)

summary(model_1)
